where γ and β are positive real constants and M may be either a positive real scalar or a positive definite matrix. The vectors x and p represent (respectively) generalized coordinates describing the system’s state and their canonically conjugate momenta, and the function U (x) is the potential energy, which is responsible for conservative forces. In our work, the quantities x and p will be mapped to (respectively) the currents and voltages in a circuit. Also, the noise term here is assumed to have a covariance matrix proportional to identity (i.e., the noise is uncorrelated), but in general we may also replace the identity matrix by another positive definite matrix to model a system coupled to a correlated noise source. Note that Eqs. (1) and (2) can be combined to yield dx = −γ−1∇U − γ−1dp + N [0, 2γ−1β−1I dt]; in the overdamped limit (where M is small and γ is large) the second term on the right can be dropped, leading to the overdamped Langevin (ODL) equation

