Langevin equations (overdamped or underdamped) are examples of SDEs, which describe a system on the level of a single trajectory. In general, the SDE that governs the stochastic trajectories of a system can be recast as a partial differential equation (PDE) that governs the time-evolution of the probability density function of the system’s state. The PDEs corresponding to the overdamped and underdamped Langevin equations are called Fokker-Planck equations, and the stationary distribution for x (which is the same for the ODL and UDL equations) is called the Gibbs distribution

